    <hedline>
      <hl1>In &#8216;Sunny Side Up,&#8217; artist Eran Shakine pokes fun at lofty notions about art</hl1>
      <hl2 hl2class="subhead"></hl2>
      <hl2 hl2class="overline">The Find</hl2>
    </hedline>
    <byline>
      
        <person>By Jan Gardner</person>
        
      
      <byttl></byttl>
    </byline>
    <abstract>In &#8220;Sunny Side Up,&#8217;&#8217; artist Eran Shakine pokes fun at lofty notions about art, inspiration, and genius. In the text below his sketch of a museum scene, Shakine notes that museum-goers spend an average of 10 seconds with each work, half of which is spent reading the label. He draws a hairpiece in the shape of, say, a Frank Gehry building and plops it on Gehry&#8217;s head. With a few bold lines, Shakine creates a world of commentary.</abstract> 
  </body.head>
  <body.content>
    <block class="txt">
      
      <p>In <em class="b">&#8220;Sunny Side Up&#8217;&#8217;</em> (Hirmer), artist Eran Shakine, who lives in Tel Aviv and London, pokes fun at lofty notions about art, inspiration, and genius. In the text below his sketch of a museum scene, Shakine notes that museumgoers spend an average of 10 seconds with each work, half of which is spent reading the label. He draws a hairpiece in the shape of, say, a Frank Gehry building and plops it on Gehry&#8217;s head. He dresses Ralph Lauren and other male fashion designers in the clothing they create for women. With a few bold lines, Shakine creates a world of commentary.</p>
      
    </block>
    
      
    
  </body.content>
